social_posts.post_text: Mural tip of the week number 29! This one is all about painting brick since I just finished a huge brick mural and it was intense. Hope you find some of these tips helpful! Next week is 30🥳

Painting the floor mural at @hatch44cafe! This was the quickest one of the 4, surprisingly. It was sealed and coated after painting (not by me) and it’s at the entrance to the cafe, in a soon to come small vestibule between the front door and the inside of the cafe. It was very nerve wracking but also very satisfying to paint this one. Stay tuned for a mural tip on floor murals (maybe it’ll be my big 30? 😄)
My last outdoor mural of the year in the Poconos ⛰️👩‍🎨
What’s the first thing that comes to mind when you think of brunch? 🍳🥞🍾
🥳🥳 it’s my 30th mural tip! All about painting a cement floor with no background color 😬 enjoy!

Sketches for a piece I did… last year I think? Sometimes you gotta sit on things for a long time before they’re out 😄 this is for one of my oldest and favorite clients @chalk_couture. Which would you pick?

I am so happy to finally be able to share this mural I created and painted for @paperplanecoffeeco in Montclair, NJ earlier this fall! I’ve been waiting until their super cool airplane seats and windows were in and they look so fantastic, worth the wait ✈️

Ladies and gentlemen, as we start our descent, please make sure your seat backs and tray tables are in their full upright position. Make sure your seat belt is securely fastened and all carry-on luggage is stowed underneath the seat in front of you or in the overhead bins. Thank you.

Lots of right guesses last time with my sketch post :) the client ended up choosing the bottom left sketch with some adjustments like making the script type straight and removing the branches and using more snowflakes instead. I show these in black on white and reverse because the final product for these pieces is a transfer on a chalkboard.
A walk through all 4 murals at @hatch44cafe in Metuchen, NJ. This was a fun series to create🥰

Mural tip of the week No.31 and Part 2 of mural packing essentials! Whoops it’s been a while since I did part 1 but here we are. Bring tiny scissors with you to cut off any stray bristles that keep messing with your clean lines ✂️ 🖌️

Final reel for my mural at @paperplanecoffeeco! I cannot wait to see it in person when they’re open because I’ve only seen it on a bare wall with nothing underneath and it looks about a million times cooler now 🤩 ✈️

Don’t think I ever posted a photo of this final mural for @hatch44cafe. Wish you could see the texture of that wall in a photo 😂 it was definitely a challenge to paint all of these thin perfect lines😅

Recap of this year’s murals actually surprised me because I didn’t know I painted 15 murals this year (4 of which were a set of smaller sidewalk murals), making my total 22 since I started a year and a half ago 🥳 thank you to everyone that made it all possible and to those that supported my business this past year ❤️ it really means a whole lot

Mural tip of the week No.32: scissor lift basics! This was a tough one to make so I hope it’s clear enough but to be honest, once you use it once you’ll get the hang of it quick, it’s pretty simple to use. I was very nervous the first time I had to use one for only my second mural ever but it was completely fine so don’t worry if you’re faced with having to use one, you’ll get used to it so quick!
Holiday card for this year! First time in a while I designed something for fun and didn’t overthink it. Wanted to also commemorate my year of murals here if you can spot it 😄👩‍🎨🎨

It’s almost Christmas! These sketches were done so long ago, I think last winter maybe even, and I can finally share the project. Another fun one for @chalk_couture! Which sketch would you go with if you were the client?

For those that guessed the first sketch, that’s the one the client chose and my favorite one too! This was turned into a transfer similar to a silkscreen that can be transferred onto chalk boards as decorations 🎄 merry Christmas Eve!

Not even sure how to share this project but it was definitely one of the most “pinch me” projects of this year so I felt like I had to share. Give you two guesses who the client was for this Christmas campaign. The inspiration was paper cutouts and the final would be wrapped around as a seamless pattern on products. The direction: to illustrate Christmas dinner scenes with different cultures around the world so these were some of them and of course I had to do a Ukrainian one cause how could I not? Unfortunately this direction did not get selected in the end but I still really enjoyed the project and got to try out some new and different illustration styles. I’ll share a few in the stories. What’s your guess? 😄🎄

Last mural tip of 2022! Number 33 is all about printing out your mural designs so make it easier to match paint chips, swatch your colors directly on the paper and keep it as a reference with you during the painting process. Thanks for following along with me this year on my mural tips. I still have a bunch of ideas for these so if you’d like to keep seeing them, let me know in the comments!

There’s no perfect starting point or time, like January 1. If you can start now, start now!  Check out episode 181, Why Everything Matters When You’re an Artist with @olgamuzician | Passion Behind The Art 181- link in bio
Happy New Year!!!

Looking up and forward to the year ahead filled with new murals and projects. I’m open for indoor murals and digital projects currently and outdoor murals starting around March/April when the weather gets warmer! Mural for @paperplanecoffeeco ✈️

Today is mural tip day but I have decided to put it on a brief hold while I figure out how to utilize them better. Really loved this project so much, it was intense and I had to create a lot in a short amount of time but they all turned out so fun☺️

Mural tip of the week #39 is all about questions. What do you ask your mural inquiry clients before quoting them for the project? Here are some of the most important questions I make sure to ask:

1. Is there a specific design direction or idea for the mural?
2. What is the wall type and material?
3. Is it interior or exterior?
4. Ask for a photo of the wall to see if there’s anything in the way.
5. What’s the wall size vs. the mural size that they want?
6. Do they have branding to see if it can inspire the mural design?
7. Is there a specific budget?
8. What’s the deadline?

These aren’t the only questions I ask but they’re ones I find the most important to start with.
What are some questions that you make sure to ask?

I’ve got some really sad news to share today.

I found out not long ago that the site of one of my first and still favorite murals ever is going to be torn down soon. Lots of emotions come with that news and I’m not really sure how to feel. I’m definitely going to really miss driving down the street and seeing this blue giant shining brightly and always feeling a bit of disbelief that I painted it. It’s a surreal kind of feeling. I’m really sad that this mural will not exist too much longer and I’m sure a lot of people in the neighborhood will feel the same. In these last few weeks, if you’re local or nearby, it would be so amazing to see your selfies with this mural before it’s gone forever. I’d love for this design to live on on another big wall somewhere. The design will be available either as is or with some updates for installation. Email me if you’ve got a wall or know someone who does! I want to find a new home for this special guy!

I have been planning on doing one of these for probably 2 years so finally got around to actually remembering to film things 😅 Not easy running your own business and being a full time mom of a small child, my memory has definitely taken a hit. Here’s a look inside what my (busy) weeks look like as a muralist and mom. Although I focused more on the work part here, the majority of my work gets done during nap time and evenings when my daughter goes to sleep. In between those times, I get what I can and am very fortunate to have my mom take care of her 2 days per week and sometimes more if I am working on a mural onsite. Mural tip 47: using the keystone function on your projector instead of skewing images into unrecognizable shapes in Photoshop. Most projectors will have this function these days, some don’t and you’ll need to skew away, but both my super cheap regular projector and my short throw have this function. The cheap projector has a much simpler version of it and doesn’t fully straighten images sometimes but my short throw does a pretty good job usually where I don’t have to skew the art at all. Check if your projector has this function is you haven’t yet.

If you told me just 5 years ago that I’d have pink hair, I would never have believed you. Change can be good and changing your mindset can be even better. It’s easy to be afraid to take a leap and keep yourself in the same place because it’s comfortable. But nothing can compare to the freedom you feel when you finally decide to stop being afraid. For many years when I was younger, I thought that having a full time job at a big corporation was the dream. I got that job at that corporation and at first I was ecstatic. But the corporate environment is not for everyone and pretty soon, I realized that this type of work is just not for me but I was afraid to leave and to take a huge leap into freelancing. It was too unpredictable, too risky, and I was averse to risk. So I stayed. And stayed and stayed. 8 years went by and I found myself completely miserable, depressed, going to so many doctors for random physical ailments that were mostly all caused by my mental state. It was a vicious cycle that I couldn’t get out of, or let myself get out of. Until I did. And I was surprised that all of these ailments magically went away and I found myself able to breathe easier and be hopeful and excited for the future. Was I immediately successful after taking this leap? Absolutely not. Did I work my butt off and figure it out eventually? Yes and I’m still doing that. Is freelancing perfect and peachy all the time? Of course not, but the positives outweigh the negatives for me. I work for myself, I choose who I want to work with and which projects I want to do, I am not chained to someone else’s whims, and I can have pride in what I do and feel that my work matters. So take that leap, do the thing you want to do, life is short and you only get one. Also pink hair is temporary and you can always change your mind if you don’t like something new.

When painting lettering, to make sure that the strokes look consistent I always paint the full stroke of the letter instead of breaking it up where there are overlaps. It’s easy to create inconsistent weights if the letter is just filled in without paying attention to the continuous stroke so the top part of the stroke above the overlap can look thicker or thinner than the bottom part. This has helped me to ensure that my letters look clean and consistent. I do the same when drawing out blockier letters, so I paint the full stem of the letter first and then add the remaining pieces once the stem is perfect.

A little behind the scenes for #muraltipoftheweek 51. I wanted to show you how I organize my mural folders because sometimes it’s helpful to see how others organize their files. 

Here are my typical mural folders within each project:
📁 Walls: showing photos of the walls taken by client or by me. I use these for reference an for mockups
📁 References: Things my client sent me to reference in my designs. This could include things like their logo, branded elements, inspiration photos they found, etc...
📁 Research: My own research images for the concepts. I keep these separate from client-sent things so I don’t get things mixed up.
📁 Sketches: Folder that includes other folders with rounds of concepts and sketches.
📁 Final Mockups: Final approved and cleaned up artwork mocked up on client’s wall. I’ll also use files from here for my transfer.
📁 Process: Split up into “Photos” and “Videos” that keeps all of my mural painting process documentation.
📁 Reels: Final reels created for posting and sharing.

I love this organization system because it keeps everything very clear and simple and I can easily find what I’m looking for later. I’d love to hear how you split up your project files, let me know in the comments below!

When I present mural sketches to clients, they look like this, mocked up on photos of the client’s wall. I design my mockups in full color because that not only makes the process faster and easier for clients, since they get to see exactly how the mural will look on the wall, but also it doesn’t lock me into something that might not work later - for example, sometimes a black and white sketch doesn’t end up translating well when color is added and I’ll end up changing the whole design for it to work so designing the full color mockups ensures that the concepts can work fully and the client can make a more definite decision. I do, of course, clean up the final choice more once all of the revisions have been added and final design is approved.

Mural tip 53!
Some important things to include in your mural contract:

1. Detailed scope of project with # of sketch revisions so there is a mutual understanding of expectations.

2. Usage rights: Your mural contract should list that you own the rights to the design of the mural and the client only has the rights for the physical mural on their wall, not the design. So if they want to, say, print your design on T-shirts, that is an extra licensing fee that is added to the project. Also, make it clear that you own full copyright to your concepts and sketches.

3. Maintenance terms: You should not be responsible for the wall wearing down or someone defacing the mural, it’s always up to the client’s to take care of the mural once it’s done. If maintenance work needs to be performed, that’s something that is typically included as an extra hourly fee on the contract, as you cannot predict how much work it would take to fix something. Consider the cost of the materials that you’d have to repurchase to match the paint colors and the time it will take you to fix any problem areas.

4. Wall permissions: Make sure to state in your contract that the client has the right to use and paint on the wall in question. By signing the agreement, the client is confirming that they do have the rights to the wall and if any problem should arise over you painting it, will be their responsibility, not yours.

5. Lift rentals: If you need to rent a lift for a project, list it as a separate daily/weekly cost on the contract, as that is typically not included in a mural fee. 

What other mural specific terms do you include in your contract?

It’s the one you’ve asked about, or at least some of you asked about. Different transfer tricks I use to see my projected images better if they’re not very visible. I’ve now learned that raw brick is the absolute worst for transferring on because it just tends to absorb light and even the brightest projector does not show up on it unless it’s actually dark around you. Things that are easily seen in daylight on a sheet rock wall will not be visible at all on raw brick. But I’ve tried different things and here are a few that work for me when transferring murals. Mural tip 57: painting around and over obstacles and uneven surfaces. It may sound obvious but the best thing to do when you have obstacles in the way is to back up and look at your design straight on. It will never look even from the side, and that’s ok, the most important thing is that it looks perfectly aligned from the front as that is how the mural is meant to be seen and it’s how people will take photos of it. With the best alignment, you can literally hide whatever is on that wall no matter how large it is.

Recently, I’ve had a lot of requests for window murals, which I tend to have kind of a love & hate relationship with. I love them because they’re usually not as crazy involved as a regular mural, although they still take a decent amount of time to install, and painting on glass is smooth as can be, but I also tend to not take on these projects because clients don’t seem to see as much value in window murals because they’re usually more temporary, plus painting on glass is so much more uncertain than painting a wall and difficult to figure out materials. It’s also not the most satisfying painting process if you’re painting from the inside and can see all of the brushstrokes against the outside light. All that said, I don’t take too many window mural projects but this one was a no brainer because it’s for a return client of mine, @stileshoneynj for their new store That Honey Place in Fords, NJ. Last year, I painted my huge garden mural for this same client. Getting to paint some colorful flowers and bees in the thick of winter was so nice and I really love how it turned out. What is inspiration and what is copying? This Is a very important mural tip for both muralists and mural clients. Twice in the last few months, I’ve had other muralists, typically from another country, come to me to tell me that they have a mural client who wants them to copy one of my murals. And while these artists seem to inherently be uncomfortable with this, they still check with me to see if I would be ok with it and when I say it’s not ok, it seems to come as an unexpected answer. 

Muralists, it’s your job to educate your clients on copyright and moral obligations. As an artist in a larger community of artists, it will not serve you well to copy someone else’s work. If a client asks you to paint a mural copy, the answer should absolutely always be no. You’re an artist, capable of designing your own original work of art.

Clients, if you really love a muralist’s work, please contact them directly rather than asking a local artist to copy their work. More often than not, the muralist will figure out a good way to get you the mural of your dreams, whether it will be by traveling to you and installing it themselves or by designing it digitally and having another artist install it locally, or even give you the option to print their design as a vinyl so that you can have it installed in your space. There is always a solution.
